Room temperature superconductors would be a little less useful than most people seem to imagine. Superconductors stop being superconducting under a combination of three factors: temperature, current carried, and magnetic field strength. On top of that, the existence of a room temperature superconductor doesn't guarantee that it's cheap or easy to manufacture.

They might be useful for transmission lines, if cheap. Motors, too, if the maximum current is large enough. I doubt it'd be useful for computing, given that most losses happen in the silicon -- and you can't really use a superconductor to create logic if it just carries current all the time.

This is a little nit picky, but you mentioned that room temperature super conductors would mean that laptops and cellphones wouldn't get hot. That isn't actually true, because current computer technology relies on semi-conductors, with variable resistances to allow for high current (a one) or low current (a zero). That variable resistance would generate heat when current passes through them.

The place where room-temperature superconductors would help the most would probably be with transmission lines, because you could then reliably transmit power across a continent with minimal loss. That would allow you to do cool things like setting up solar panels in different time zones to transmit power from sunlit areas to nighttime areas (i.e. France to China when it is daytime in France and nighttime in China).
